Sat at the pier. I can tell I’m more concentrated/mindful now because I can hear with an awareness unconsciously. It’s almost like being underwater. I can hear the boats wheezing alongside the dock.
But I also hear my ego, and fear mania. 

I had a sense that was quite silly. I saw cars on the FDR go by. A couple at first. At a snail pace. See. Gone. See. Gone. I got excited. Then more seemed to come. More thoughts and more cars. 

My throat hurts. My heart skips a beat. My hands are cold. My phone beeps in my ear.

I prayed to god but see the stay puff marshmallow man. 
I wished for energy here, at this pier, and wondered at some rationalization of energy that took me on trains of thought filled with ego bliss and worldly

entry:
Outside in the rain, under the porch I sat on my skateboard and worked on my posture as best it could be in these old tight ass jeans.

The trees expand in front of me all dark and green. My mind is very active so I let it lead the procession, always keeping my discursive voice with me and not minding that it comes along. 

I concentrate on breathing and for a minute get caught up in a modern art figure ground swap with the streets, grass and sidewalks in the distance becoming the railing in front of me. 

I welcome what comes in. Fear around the cabinet I just put up. What if it falls. What if it hurts my children. What if I’m to blame.

Work stress pops in at the end, after the bell. Welcome, work stress. So thankful to have you here. Welcome.




Early my posture comes in. Right before the bell I hrecogbize my discursive overactive mind. I thank it for being here. For showing up. Thank you. Thank you for leading thisbporcocession. Thank you.
title: Mindfullness of Breath
